VALUES
-- Prop Trading (1)
('prop-trading-vs-classic-brokerage', 'Prop Trading vs Classic Brokerage: Comparison', 'Detailed comparison of two business models: prop trading and classic brokerage. Revenue potential, risks, and target audience.', '<h2>Business Model Fundamentals</h2><p>Classic brokerage earns from spreads, commissions, and swap fees on client trading activity. Prop trading companies earn from challenge fees and a share of trader profits. The revenue dynamics are fundamentally different: brokerages need high trading volumes from many clients, while prop firms need a large funnel of challenge purchasers with a manageable number of funded traders generating consistent returns.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6770610/pexels-photo-6770610.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Prop vs Brokerage" /><h2>Revenue and Risk Profiles</h2><p>Brokerage revenue is more predictable but requires substantial upfront investment in technology, licensing, and liquidity. Prop trading can start with lower capital requirements but carries the risk of funding skilled traders who generate losses. The challenge fee model provides upfront cash flow, but firms must carefully manage the ratio of challenge revenue to funded trader payouts.</p><h2>Hybrid Approach</h2><p>Many companies now offer both services. Existing brokers add prop trading modules to attract a new client segment. This hybrid model leverages shared infrastructure while diversifying revenue streams. The key challenge is managing potential conflicts between broker clients and funded traders competing in the same market.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6770610/pexels-photo-6770610.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Prop Trading', ARRAY['prop trading', 'brokerage', 'comparison', 'business model', 'hybrid', 'challenge'], 7, 'Prop Trading vs Classic Brokerage', 'Comparing prop trading and classic brokerage business models. Revenue and risks.', true, now()),

-- Binary Options (3)
('crypto-binary-options-trading', 'Binary Options on Cryptocurrencies: New Trend', 'How binary options on cryptocurrencies work: volatility features, strategies, and risks of crypto options trading.', '<h2>Why Crypto Binary Options Are Growing</h2><p>Cryptocurrency volatility makes it an attractive underlying asset for binary options. Bitcoin can move 3-5% in a single session, providing ample opportunity for directional trades. Crypto binary options are available 24/7, unlike traditional forex options limited to market hours. This accessibility combined with the growing crypto market has created significant demand among retail traders.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/7567444/pexels-photo-7567444.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Crypto Binary Options" /><h2>Trading Strategies</h2><p>Successful crypto binary options trading requires understanding both crypto market dynamics and options mechanics. Trend-following strategies work well during strong directional moves driven by news events. Range-bound strategies suit periods of consolidation between major support and resistance levels. Always account for the higher implied volatility of crypto assets when selecting expiration times.</p><h2>Risk Considerations</h2><p>Crypto binary options carry amplified risks: the inherent binary risk of total loss on each trade combined with cryptocurrency''s extreme volatility and susceptibility to manipulation. Traders should use strict money management, never risking more than 1-2% per trade, and be aware that crypto markets can gap significantly during low-liquidity periods.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/7567444/pexels-photo-7567444.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Binary Options', ARRAY['cryptocurrencies', 'binary options', 'Bitcoin', 'volatility', 'crypto options', 'trading'], 7, 'Binary Options on Cryptocurrencies', 'Crypto binary options: features, strategies, and risks of trading crypto options.', true, now()),

('binary-options-regulation-worldwide', 'Binary Options Regulation Around the World', 'Overview of the regulatory landscape for binary options: bans, restrictions, and jurisdictions where trading is permitted.', '<h2>European Ban and Its Impact</h2><p>ESMA permanently banned binary options marketing and sale to retail clients across the EU in 2018, following temporary restrictions. The UK''s FCA implemented a similar prohibition. This regulatory action was driven by documented losses exceeding 80% among retail binary options traders and widespread fraudulent practices by unregulated operators targeting European clients.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6771607/pexels-photo-6771607.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Binary Options Regulation" /><h2>Permitted Jurisdictions</h2><p>Binary options remain legal and regulated in several jurisdictions. The US permits exchange-traded binary options through CFTC-regulated platforms like Nadex. Japan and Australia allow regulated binary options with specific conditions. Offshore jurisdictions including Vanuatu and the Marshall Islands license binary options brokers, though with less stringent oversight.</p><h2>Compliance Requirements</h2><p>Operators in regulated jurisdictions must meet specific requirements: segregated client funds, maximum payout and loss limits, mandatory risk warnings, and restrictions on marketing practices. Some jurisdictions require minimum trade durations to prevent turbo options. Staying compliant requires ongoing monitoring of regulatory changes across all markets where you operate.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6771607/pexels-photo-6771607.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Binary Options', ARRAY['regulation', 'binary options', 'ESMA', 'CySEC', 'license', 'ban'], 8, 'Binary Options Regulation Worldwide', 'Regulatory landscape for binary options. Bans in EU and permitted jurisdictions.', true, now()),

('turbo-options-strategies-tips', 'Turbo Options: Strategies and Tips for Traders', 'How to trade turbo options with 30-120 second expiration: scalping strategies, asset selection, and emotional control.', '<h2>Understanding Turbo Options</h2><p>Turbo options expire in 30 to 120 seconds, requiring instant decision-making and precise timing. These ultra-short contracts demand a different approach than standard binary options. Success depends on reading micro-trends within larger price movements, identifying momentum shifts at key support and resistance levels, and executing trades within narrow windows of opportunity.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/5980888/pexels-photo-5980888.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Turbo Options" /><h2>Effective Turbo Strategies</h2><p>Momentum trading works best for turbo options: enter in the direction of a strong candle breakout from consolidation. Use 5-second and 15-second charts with RSI and Bollinger Bands for confirmation. Avoid trading during choppy, directionless markets. Focus on high-volume sessions (London/New York overlap) when price movements are most decisive.</p><h2>Psychological Discipline</h2><p>The rapid pace of turbo options trading amplifies emotional responses. Losses feel more intense and the temptation to chase recovery trades is strong. Set strict daily limits: maximum number of trades, maximum loss amount, and mandatory breaks after losing streaks. Many successful turbo traders limit themselves to 10-15 trades per session to maintain focus and discipline.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/5980888/pexels-photo-5980888.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Binary Options', ARRAY['turbo options', 'scalping', 'strategies', 'psychology', 'discipline', 'binary options'], 6, 'Turbo Options: Strategies and Tips', 'Trading turbo options: scalping strategies, asset selection, and emotional control.', true, now()),

-- Brokers (4)
('how-to-choose-broker-checklist-15', 'How to Choose a Broker: 15-Point Checklist', 'What to look for when choosing a broker: regulation, trading conditions, reliability, and potential pitfalls.', '<h2>Regulatory and Safety Checks</h2><p>Points 1-5 cover safety fundamentals: verify active regulatory license on the regulator''s official website, confirm client fund segregation in separate bank accounts, check participation in compensation schemes (up to 20,000 EUR under CySEC ICF), review the broker''s operating history (minimum 3 years preferred), and investigate any regulatory actions or sanctions.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6801642/pexels-photo-6801642.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Broker Checklist" /><h2>Trading Conditions</h2><p>Points 6-10 evaluate trading quality: compare real spreads during active market hours, test execution speed and slippage rates, review available instruments and account types, check leverage options and margin requirements, and verify there are no hidden restrictions on trading strategies like scalping or hedging.</p><h2>Service and Support</h2><p>Points 11-15 assess the overall experience: test customer support responsiveness across channels, evaluate the quality and speed of the deposit/withdrawal process, review educational resources and market analysis, check mobile platform functionality, and verify transparent fee disclosure including swap rates, inactivity fees, and withdrawal charges.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6801642/pexels-photo-6801642.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Brokers', ARRAY['broker selection', 'regulation', 'reliability', 'trading conditions', 'checklist'], 14, 'How to Choose a Broker: 15-Point Checklist', 'Detailed guide to choosing a broker. Regulation, safety, trading conditions, and red flags.', true, now()),

('cryptocurrency-brokerage-features', 'Cryptocurrency Brokerage: Features and Advantages', 'How to open a cryptocurrency broker: requirements, technologies, and features of crypto brokerage operations.', '<h2>Crypto Brokerage vs Traditional Forex</h2><p>Cryptocurrency brokerage differs from traditional forex in several key ways: 24/7 market operations, integration with blockchain networks for deposits and withdrawals, custody requirements for digital assets, and rapidly evolving regulatory frameworks. The technology stack must handle both traditional trading infrastructure and blockchain-specific components.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/8358026/pexels-photo-8358026.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Crypto Brokerage" /><h2>Technical Requirements</h2><p>A crypto brokerage needs connections to major exchanges and OTC desks for liquidity, wallet infrastructure supporting multiple blockchains, real-time price aggregation engines, and blockchain analytics tools for compliance. Many brokers start by offering crypto CFDs before adding spot trading with actual cryptocurrency delivery.</p><h2>Competitive Advantages</h2><p>Crypto brokerages that succeed differentiate through superior liquidity (tight spreads across more trading pairs), advanced security (insurance funds, proof of reserves), educational content helping traditional traders transition to crypto, and innovative products like tokenized assets, staking services, and DeFi access through a familiar brokerage interface.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/8358026/pexels-photo-8358026.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Brokers', ARRAY['cryptocurrencies', 'Bitcoin', 'Ethereum', 'crypto broker', 'blockchain'], 10, 'Cryptocurrency Brokerage: Complete Guide', 'How to open a crypto broker. Advantages, requirements, and exchange integration.', true, now()),

('top-10-brokerage-business-trends-2024', 'Top 10 Brokerage Business Trends in 2024', 'Key trends shaping the brokerage business: AI, cryptocurrencies, mobile trading, social trading, and regulatory changes.', '<h2>Technology-Driven Trends</h2><p>Artificial intelligence is transforming every aspect of brokerage operations: from AI-powered client support chatbots and automated compliance screening to algorithmic risk management and personalized trading recommendations. Mobile-first platforms now process over 70% of retail trades, while API-driven architectures enable rapid integration of new services and liquidity sources.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/7681097/pexels-photo-7681097.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Brokerage Trends" /><h2>Product Innovation</h2><p>Social and copy trading continue growing, with platforms reporting 40% year-over-year increase in copy trading volumes. Prop trading integration into traditional brokerages creates new revenue streams. Fractional share trading democratizes access to expensive stocks. Crypto asset integration becomes standard rather than optional as client demand for digital asset exposure accelerates.</p><h2>Regulatory Evolution</h2><p>Stricter global regulation is reshaping the competitive landscape. MiCA implementation in Europe, ongoing SEC scrutiny in the US, and new frameworks in Asia-Pacific create compliance challenges but also opportunities for well-prepared brokers. ESG-focused investment products and sustainability reporting requirements are emerging as the next wave of regulatory expectations.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/7681097/pexels-photo-7681097.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Brokers', ARRAY['trends', 'brokers', 'AI', 'cryptocurrencies', 'mobile trading'], 8, 'Top 10 Brokerage Trends 2024', 'Key brokerage business trends: AI, crypto, mobile trading, social trading, and regulation.', true, now()),

('risk-management-a-book-vs-b-book', 'A-Book vs B-Book Risk Management in Brokerage', 'Comparing A-Book and B-Book order execution models: advantages, disadvantages, and the hybrid approach.', '<h2>Understanding A-Book Model</h2><p>In the A-Book (STP/ECN) model, the broker routes all client orders directly to liquidity providers, earning revenue solely from commissions and spread markups. This eliminates conflict of interest with clients but limits profit potential. A-Book requires robust liquidity provider relationships and sophisticated order routing technology to ensure competitive execution.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6802042/pexels-photo-6802042.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="A-Book vs B-Book" /><h2>B-Book Model Dynamics</h2><p>The B-Book model internalizes client orders, with the broker acting as counterparty. Revenue comes from client trading losses in addition to spreads. While more profitable per client, this creates inherent conflict of interest and requires sophisticated risk management to hedge aggregate exposure. Regulatory scrutiny of B-Book practices continues to increase globally.</p><h2>Hybrid Risk Management</h2><p>Most successful brokers implement hybrid models. Profitable, experienced traders are routed A-Book to liquidity providers. Smaller, less experienced accounts stay B-Book where statistical advantages favor the broker. Sophisticated risk engines analyze real-time trading patterns to dynamically categorize and route orders. The hybrid approach optimizes revenue while managing exposure.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6802042/pexels-photo-6802042.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Brokers', ARRAY['A-Book', 'B-Book', 'risks', 'liquidity', 'execution'], 10, 'A-Book vs B-Book: Broker Risk Management', 'Comparing A-Book and B-Book models. Advantages, disadvantages, and hybrid approach.', true, now()),

-- Trading Bots (3)
('algorithmic-trading-api-solutions', 'API for Algorithmic Trading: Solutions Overview', 'Comparing APIs for connecting trading algorithms: REST, FIX, WebSocket protocols and latency optimization.', '<h2>Protocol Comparison</h2><p>Three primary protocols serve algorithmic trading: FIX (Financial Information eXchange) is the industry standard for institutional trading with sub-millisecond latency. REST APIs provide easy integration for strategy prototyping and medium-frequency trading. WebSocket connections offer real-time data streaming with lower overhead than polling-based REST approaches. Protocol choice depends on strategy frequency and latency requirements.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6771607/pexels-photo-6771607.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Trading API" /><h2>Implementation Considerations</h2><p>Python dominates algo trading development for its rich ecosystem (pandas, NumPy, scikit-learn) and rapid prototyping capabilities. C++ and Java serve high-frequency strategies where microsecond optimization matters. Regardless of language, implement robust error handling, connection recovery, and order state reconciliation to prevent costly failures during production trading.</p><h2>Latency Optimization</h2><p>For latency-sensitive strategies, co-locate servers in the same data center as the broker''s matching engine. Use kernel bypass networking and lock-free data structures. Pre-compute order parameters to minimize processing time at execution signals. Monitor tick-to-trade latency continuously and establish baselines for performance regression detection.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6771607/pexels-photo-6771607.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Trading Bots', ARRAY['API', 'algorithmic trading', 'FIX', 'REST', 'WebSocket', 'Python', 'algo trading'], 8, 'API for Algorithmic Trading', 'Overview of APIs for algo trading. FIX, REST, WebSocket and latency optimization.', true, now()),

('backtesting-trading-strategies-guide', 'Backtesting Trading Strategies: Tools and Methods', 'How to properly test trading strategies on historical data: tools, methodology, and common optimization traps.', '<h2>Backtesting Fundamentals</h2><p>Backtesting validates trading strategies against historical market data before risking real capital. Quality backtesting requires tick-level data (not just OHLC candles), realistic spread and commission modeling, slippage simulation, and proper handling of gaps, dividends, and corporate actions. The goal is to simulate live trading conditions as accurately as possible.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6801874/pexels-photo-6801874.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Backtesting" /><h2>Tools and Platforms</h2><p>MetaTrader''s Strategy Tester provides basic backtesting for EA developers. Python with Backtrader or Zipline offers flexibility for custom strategies. QuantConnect and TradingView provide cloud-based backtesting with extensive data libraries. For institutional strategies, commercial platforms like MultiCharts and NinjaTrader offer tick-level precision and multi-asset support.</p><h2>Avoiding Common Traps</h2><p>Overfitting is the most dangerous pitfall: optimizing parameters to fit historical data perfectly while creating a strategy that fails in live markets. Combat overfitting by using out-of-sample testing periods, walk-forward optimization, and Monte Carlo simulations. Validate results across different market regimes (trending, ranging, volatile) to ensure robustness.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6801874/pexels-photo-6801874.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Trading Bots', ARRAY['backtesting', 'testing', 'strategies', 'optimization', 'algo trading', 'historical data'], 9, 'Backtesting Trading Strategies: Guide', 'Tools and methods for backtesting trading strategies. Optimization traps and validation.', true, now()),

('automatic-trade-copying-systems', 'Automatic Trade Copying: Systems and Setup', 'How trade copying systems work: social trading, PAMM and MAM accounts, choosing signal providers, and risk management.', '<h2>Trade Copying Technologies</h2><p>Modern trade copying operates through three main systems: Social trading platforms where followers automatically replicate leader trades in real time. PAMM (Percentage Allocation Money Management) accounts where a manager trades a pooled fund with proportional profit distribution. MAM (Multi-Account Manager) accounts allowing professional managers to execute trades across multiple sub-accounts simultaneously.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/5980888/pexels-photo-5980888.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Trade Copying" /><h2>Choosing Signal Providers</h2><p>Evaluate signal providers using statistical metrics beyond raw returns: Sharpe ratio for risk-adjusted performance, maximum drawdown for worst-case scenarios, average trade duration for strategy classification, and consistency of returns across different market conditions. A minimum 12-month track record with at least 200 trades provides sufficient data for meaningful analysis.</p><h2>Risk Management for Copiers</h2><p>Never allocate all capital to a single signal provider. Diversify across 3-5 uncorrelated strategies. Set maximum drawdown limits per provider and automatic disconnection triggers. Adjust copy proportions based on your risk tolerance rather than blindly following position sizes. Regularly review provider performance and replace underperforming or style-drifting sources.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/5980888/pexels-photo-5980888.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Trading Bots', ARRAY['trade copying', 'social trading', 'PAMM', 'MAM', 'signals', 'investments'], 8, 'Automatic Trade Copying Systems', 'How trade copying works on forex. PAMM, MAM, and social trading.', true, now()),

-- Trading (3)
('copy-trading-guide-earning', 'Copy Trading: Earning by Copying Successful Traders', 'What is copy trading and how does it work? Choosing traders to copy, risk management, and best practices.', '<h2>How Copy Trading Works</h2><p>Copy trading platforms connect experienced traders with followers who automatically replicate their positions. When a lead trader opens, modifies, or closes a position, the same action executes proportionally in all follower accounts. This democratizes access to professional trading strategies for those who lack the time or expertise to trade independently.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6772076/pexels-photo-6772076.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Copy Trading" /><h2>Selecting Traders to Copy</h2><p>Look beyond headline returns when selecting traders. Prioritize consistent monthly performance over explosive but volatile results. Evaluate maximum drawdown, average trade holding period, and risk-reward ratios. Prefer traders who have demonstrated profitability across different market conditions for at least 12 months with verified track records on regulated platforms.</p><h2>Building a Copy Portfolio</h2><p>Treat copy trading like portfolio management. Allocate capital across multiple traders with different strategies, instruments, and time horizons. A conservative trader, a trend follower, and a breakout specialist provide natural diversification. Monitor aggregate portfolio exposure to avoid unintended concentration in correlated positions, especially during major market events.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6772076/pexels-photo-6772076.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Trading', ARRAY['copy trading', 'social trading', 'copying', 'passive income', 'investments'], 13, 'Copy Trading: Complete Guide', 'How to earn by copying successful traders. Selection, risk management, and best practices.', true, now()),

('forex-vs-stocks-vs-crypto-markets', 'Forex vs Stocks vs Crypto: Market Comparison', 'Which market to choose for trading? Detailed comparison of forex, stock market, and cryptocurrencies.', '<h2>Market Characteristics</h2><p>Forex offers the highest liquidity ($6.6 trillion daily volume), 24/5 trading, and leverage up to 1:500. Stocks provide ownership in real companies with dividends and voting rights but limited trading hours. Cryptocurrencies combine 24/7 accessibility with extreme volatility and emerging technology exposure. Each market has distinct risk-return profiles suited to different trading styles.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6801642/pexels-photo-6801642.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Market Comparison" /><h2>Cost Comparison</h2><p>Forex trading costs are primarily spread-based, typically $3-$15 per standard lot on major pairs. Stock trading involves commissions ($0-$10 per trade depending on broker), exchange fees, and wider spreads on less liquid names. Crypto trading fees range from 0.1-0.5% per trade on exchanges, with additional network fees for on-chain transactions.</p><h2>Which Market Suits You</h2><p>Day traders and scalpers often prefer forex for its liquidity and tight spreads. Long-term investors gravitate toward stocks for fundamental value creation. Crypto attracts those seeking high growth potential and technological disruption exposure. Many experienced traders diversify across all three markets, adapting their strategies to each market''s unique characteristics.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6801642/pexels-photo-6801642.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Trading', ARRAY['forex', 'stocks', 'cryptocurrencies', 'comparison', 'market selection'], 10, 'Forex vs Stocks vs Crypto: Comparison', 'Detailed comparison of forex, stocks, and crypto. Costs, advantages, and which suits you.', true, now()),

('trading-psychology-mastering-emotions', 'Trading Psychology: Mastering Emotions in Markets', 'Why 90% of traders lose money: key psychological mistakes and how to avoid them through discipline and strategy.', '<h2>The Emotional Trading Cycle</h2><p>Most traders experience a predictable emotional cycle: excitement during winning streaks leads to overconfidence and increased position sizes. Inevitable losses trigger fear and hesitation, causing missed opportunities. Frustration from missed moves leads to revenge trading with poor setups. Breaking this cycle requires systematic approaches that remove emotion from trading decisions.</p><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/6802049/pexels-photo-6802049.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800" alt="Trading Psychology" /><h2>FOMO and Loss Aversion</h2><p>Fear of Missing Out drives traders into positions without proper analysis, especially during strong trending moves. Loss aversion causes traders to hold losing positions too long (hoping for recovery) while cutting winners too early (locking in small gains). Both biases destroy the positive risk-reward ratios that profitable strategies require.</p><h2>Building Emotional Discipline</h2><p>Develop and follow a written trading plan with specific entry, exit, and position sizing rules. Keep a trading journal documenting not just trades but the emotions and thoughts behind each decision. Set daily loss limits and walk away when reached. Meditation, regular exercise, and adequate sleep significantly improve decision-making quality under market pressure.</p>', 'https://images.pexels.com/photos/6802049/pexels-photo-6802049.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800', 'en', true, 'MakeTrades Team', 'Trading', ARRAY['psychology', 'emotions', 'FOMO', 'discipline', 'strategy'], 9, 'Trading Psychology: Controlling Emotions', 'Key psychological traps for traders and ways to overcome them. Practical tips for successful trading.', true, now());